article.description:
Eddie House shot the Miami Heat to a 
crucial win in the Philadelphia 76ers' house.
article.headline: Despite Iverson's 38, teams split home-and-home series
article.linkText: Red-hot House gets Heat past Sixers in Philly
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Miami Heat are unbeaten in the second night of back-to-back games. A well-rested Eddie House made the difference Wednesday night against the 76ers.
House

A night after he played just 15 minutes and shot 0-for-3, House came off the bench to score a season-high 20 points and lead the Heat to a 82-77 victory over Philadelphia. With the teams tied at 75 late in the fourth, House nailed a 3-pointer from 29 feet, then followed with a 12-foot jumper on the next possession to give the Heat a 80-75 edge. He hit a pair of foul shots with 8.3 seconds remaining to clinch the win after a tight fourth quarter that featured seven ties. "He was the difference," said fellow reserve Chris Gatling, who scored 13. "When he's on fire, he's hard to stop. Tonight, he was fabulous." The Sixers missed three off-balance shots on their final possession with under 30 seconds to play, including a 3-point attempt by Eric Snow that would have tied the game. Allen Iverson finished with 38 points for Philadelphia, a bucket short of what would have been his 10th 40-point game of the season. The stellar play of the Heat's bench was the difference in a rough contest with 41 fouls. The Heat got 36 points from their reserves to Philadelphia's 10. Five Heat players were in double digits. Alonzo Mourning had 16 and Rod Strickland 14. House's previous season-high was 17. For the Sixers, only Matt Harpring, with 15, joined Iverson in double figures. Injuries were one reason why. The Sixers were without forward Derrick Coleman, who sat a day after he was diagnosed with torn cartilage in his knee. He scored 20 points playing with the injury Tuesday. Iverson said his teammates have to do more to fill the void. "People are supposed to love the opportunity to be able to play. When you don't play all year and then you have an opportunity to get quality minutes, that is your chance ... You shouldn't even be able to sleep the night before." Miami needed the win to stay within striking distance of the Charlotte Hornets for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. The Sixers fell two games behind Orlando for fifth place in the East. The win wasn't sweet enough for Heat coach Pat Riley, who was still bitter over the team's 91-79 loss to the Sixers on Tuesday night at Miami in the first half of the back-to-back series. "For some reason, it always takes a humiliating loss to correct things, and I have to do something about it," Riley said. "We just don't take advantage when we have an edge." It was Miami's first victory against the Sixers this season in four tries. The Heat are 11-0 in the second game of back-to-backs. Philadelphia ran into foul trouble early. Dikembe Mutombo was called for his fourth with 9:39 left in the third. He returned in the fourth, but finished with three points. The first quarter featured eight lead changes. Harpring had 11 points in the first to pace the Sixers to a 22-19 edge. Miami pulled away in the second behind the shooting of House and Chris Gatling and built a 45-35 lead. Iverson had 20 points on 7-of-14 shooting to cut Miami's lead to 45-38 at the half. The Sixers went on an 8-0 run early in the third, culminating with Speedy Claxton's steal and layup to cut the Miami edge to 51-50 with 7:19 left in the quarter. Iverson hit two foul shots with four seconds left to put the Sixers up 61-60, giving them their first lead since the first minute of the second period. But Jim Jackson hit a 3 from the corner as time expired to put Miami up by two at the end of three quarters. Game notes
The Sixers Aaron McKie sat out for the 22nd time in 25 games with a sprained left ankle. ...Coleman's replacement, Corie Blount, had to leave the game briefly for an X-ray in the first after he was struck in the nose by Mutombo. ... Twelve of Miami's remaining 16 games are against winning teams. ...Heat point guard Anthony Carter missed the game while awaiting the birth of his first child.
